commit_message:
Root LayoutNode to behave as a Stack

This means we will measure the direct children with loosen constraints (minWidth and minHeight = 0) instead of behaving as if Modifier.fillMaxSize() was already applied as it proven to be not predictable and making writing any sample projects a bit too complex. Almost always you have to start with something like
setContent {
    Stack {
        Button()
    }
}
instead of just directly emit Button without a Stack. When you wrote
setContent {
    Button()
}
You probably didn't mean I wanted to fill the whole screen with a huge Button. Put a default sized Button into a left top corner of the screen seems like a more reasonable default

Relnote: We changed how we measure the first layout you put inside activity.setContent { } block. Previously it was forced to fill the whole activity screen, and now it behaves as if you put your layout inside a Stack: it can be smaller than a screen and will be positioned in the top left screen. If you want the old behaviour you can apply Modifier.fillMaxSize() for your layout.
Bug: 153453714
Test: manually, new tests
Change-Id: Ie88a713401b8d1db32acf421f2612121bd1d23f6

Desktop. Composable Window API. Window

- low-level composable AwtWindow(create = {}, dispose = {}, update = {}).
Is used by Dialog and Window.

- low-level Window(create = {}, dispose = {}, update = {}, content={})
It composes content into ComposeWindow.

- high-level Window:
```
val state = rememberWindowState(
    size = WindowSize(200.dp, 200.dp),
    isMaximized = true
)
Window(state, resizable = false, undecorated = true, alwaysOnTop = true) {
    Button(onClick = { state.isOpen = false }) {
        Text("Close")
    }
}
```
Provides user-friendly parameters to change properties of the window.

- Window provides WindowScope.window: ComposeWindow.
Generally it is better than LocalWindow - we strictly control who can access this window.

- Hoisted WindowState. Provides ability to change/observe size/position/status/visibility.
We didn't introduce Modifier, because:
-- size/position in 95% of cases should be controlled by Window Manager, not by application
-- we don't have a real parent in which we can layout our Window (we can have multiple screens)
-- Modifier usually is coupled with LayoutNode

- WindowState provides implicit state isOpen. Because we have implicit state, we can write a cleaner code in some cases:
```
fun main() = application {
  Window {
  }
}
```
instead of:
```
var isOpen by mutableStateOf(true)

fun main() = application {
    if (isOpen) {
        Window(onCloseRequest = { isOpen = false }) {
        }
    }
}
```

Downside - if we use our own state, we will have two sources of truth
and can forget to sync this state with the internal state.

See discussion here:
https://android-review.googlesource.com/c/platform/frameworks/support/+/1674523/4..14/compose/desktop/desktop/samples/src/jvmMain/kotlin/androidx/compose/desktop/examples/windowapi/Examples.jvm.kt#b109

Discussion of API and demos: https://android-review.googlesource.com/c/platform/frameworks/support/+/1674523
(See examples: helloWorld, splashScreen, autoClose, changingOpenState, askToClose, closeToTray, nestedWindow,
customWindow, setIcon, setParameters, setPosition, initiallyCenteredWindow, setSize, setStatus, hotKeys)

